Supporting material for the article

A Robust Optimization Approach to the Next Release Problem in the Presence of Uncertainties

By Matheus Paixao, Jerffeson Souza
Optimization in Software Engineering Group (GOES.UECE)
State University of Ceara - Brazil

November 2013 (last update: November 2013)

Table of Contents
  1. Abstract
  2. Instances
    1. Synthetical Instances
    2. Real-world Instances
  3. Source Code

Abstract

The next release problem is a significant task in the iterative and incremental software development model, involving the selection of a set of requirements to be included in the next software release. Given the dynamic environment in which modern software development occurs, the uncertainties related to the input variables of this problem should be taken into account. In this context, this paper presents a formulation to the next release problem considering the robust optimization framework, which enables the production of robust solutions. In order to measure the “price of robustness”, which is the loss in solution quality due to robustness, a large empirical evaluation was executed over synthetical and real-world instances. Several next release planning situations were considered, including different number of requirements, estimating skills and interdependencies between requirements. All empirical results are consistent to show that the penalization with regard to solution quality is relatively small. In addition, the proposed model’s behavior is statistically the same for all considered instances, which qualifies it to be applied even in large-scale real-world software projects.

Next Release Problem, Robust Optimization, Search Based Software Engineering.

Instances

Synthetical Instances

The synthetical instances were generated with a different number of requirements, represented by {50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400, 450, 500}, respectively. Each instance has 2, 3 or 4 scenarios, randomly choosed. The probability of each scenario was also defined at random. The requirements’ importance values can assume an integer between 1 and 10. The effort cost estimates also vary from 1 to 10. Different cost variations strategies were considered. The cost variation was set to one of the following values {10%, 20%, 30%, 40%, 50%}. A cost variation of 10% means that each cost variation is considered to be 10% of the respective requirement estimated cost. A random approach was also introduced, where each requirement cost variation is independently generated as a random number between 0 and 50% of the estimated cost. The precedence density between requirements assumes one of the following values {0, 10%, 20%}. The precedence density indicates the percentage of requirements which will have precedence. In that case, the requirement will have, as precedents, between 1 and 5% of other requirements, which is established randomly. All possible next release planning aspects described above (number of requirements, cost variation strategy and precedence density) were combined, resulting in a set with 180 synthetical instances. The synthetical instances names are in the format I_S_R_C_P, where R represents the number of requirements, C indicates the cost variation strategy and P denotes the precedence density.

Real-world Instances

The real-world instances were adapted from Xuan et al. In that paper, the instances to the NRP were extracted from bug repositories of three big open source projects, including Eclipse (a java integrated development environment) and Mozilla (a set of web applications). A bug repository is a forum where users (end users, developers, testers, etc) can report bugs related to the project. Each bug is then considered as a requirement. In this forum, one bug report may be commented by many users. Each requirement importance value is then calculated as the number of users that commented on that particular bug report, which represents the only possible scenario. In addition, the bug severity is mapped to the requirement cost estimate. Both the requirement’s importance and cost are normalized to fall into the 1 to 10 interval. Several instances were extracted from each bug repository. They are composed only by the most important requirements. The number of requirements of the real-world instances are {20, 50, 100, 150, 200}, respectively. Regarding the cost variation, the same strategies used in the synthetical instances were also applied to the real ones. Since bugs are usually independent from each other, there is no precedence relationships in the real instances. Therefore, the combination of the possible aspects of the real instances, such as bug repositories, number of requirements and cost variation strategies, resulted in 60 real-world NRP instances. The real instances names are in the format I_Re_P_R_C, where P represents the project (E for Eclipse and M for Mozilla), R is the number of requirements and C is the cost variation strategy.

Source Code

The source code used in the empirical study can be downloaded by clicking here.

The classes available in the link above are the strictly necessary classes to replicate the empirical study.

Once in the bin directory, one can run the program by typing in the command line:
java ExecuteMetahframe [algorithm] rnrp [number of runs] [number of fitness evaluations] [list of instances]

Example: run the genetic algorithm for 10 times, 1000 generations for the synthetical instance I_S_100_10_50:
java ExecuteMetahframe ga rnrp 10 1000 I_S_100_10_50.txt


For other search techiniques and other problems, one can visit my github profile :)
https://github.com/mhepaixao/metahframe
